14 WHEREAS, determined to challenge systemic discrimination, he filed the landmark
15 class-action lawsuit Sagers v. Yellow Freight System in 1972 under the Civil Rights Act of
16 1964, exposing discriminatory hiring practices and securing a legal victory that helped
17 dismantle racial inequalities in the trucking industry; and
18 WHEREAS, his courageous legal battle garnered national attention and was championed by
19 civil rights activists, labor unions, and renowned attorneys such as Donald Hollowell, Jack
20 Greenberg, Elizabeth Rindskopf, and William L. Robinson, setting a legal precedent for
21 future employment discrimination cases; and
22 WHEREAS, Richard B. Sagers passed away on February 24, 1993, at the age of 59, leaving
23 behind a legacy of courage and determination that lives on through his wife, Betty; his
24 daughter, Veronica; and his grandchildren; and
25 WHEREAS, he was a person of magnanimous strengths with an unimpeachable reputation
26 for integrity, intelligence, fairness, and kindness, and by the example he made of his life, he
27 made this world a better place in which to live.
28 NOW, THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES that
29 the members of this body join in honoring the life and memory of Richard B. Sagers upon
30 the 32nd anniversary of his passing for his historic contributions to civil rights, racial
31 equality, and his country.
32 BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that the Clerk of the House of Representatives is authorized
33 and directed to make an appropriate copy of this resolution available for distribution to the
34 family of Richard B. Sagers.
